# TSL node chaining

In `three/tsl` shader code, prefer **method chaining on nodes** over standalone function wrappers.

```ts
// prefer
distance(a, b).smoothstep(0, range).oneMinus();
result.xy.clamp(-1, 1);
uniform.oneMinus();

// avoid
smoothstep(float(0), range, distance(a, b));
clamp(result.xy, float(-1), float(1));
float(1).sub(uniform);
```

Chain further when it reads left-to-right: `.mul()`, `.add()`, `.div()`, `.pow()`, `.mix()`, etc.

Keep standalone imports only when chaining is awkward (e.g. `Fn`, `If`, `texture`, `uniform`, `uv`) or no chain method exists.
